  "prompt": "Is calibri with font size 9 good for resume?",
  "response": "While Calibri size 9 *can* be used, it's **generally not recommended** for resumes. Here's why:\n\n*   **Readability:** Size 9 can be quite small, especially for recruiters or hiring managers who may have vision issues or be quickly scanning through many resumes. You want your resume to be easily readable.\n\n*   **Appearance:** It can make your resume look cramped and less professional.\n\n*   **ATS Compatibility:** Although generally compatible, very small fonts can sometimes cause parsing issues with Applicant Tracking Systems (ATS).\n\n**Better Alternatives:**\n\n*   **Recommended Range:** A font size between **10.5 and 12 points** is usually ideal for the body text of a resume.\n\n*   **Headings:** Use larger font sizes (14-16 points) for headings to create a clear visual hierarchy.\n\n*   **Experiment with Font Size:** You can adjust the font size slightly depending on the content and the overall layout of your resume to ensure it looks balanced and easy to read.\n\n**If you *must* use a smaller font:**\n\n*   **Prioritize Readability Above All Else:** Before submitting, print your resume and ask someone with average or less than perfect vision to read it. If they struggle, increase the font size.\n*   **Maximize White Space:** Use ample margins and spacing to avoid a cluttered look.\n*   **Consider a Different Font:** While Calibri is generally accepted, other fonts might appear larger at the same point size. Explore fonts like Arial, Times New Roman, or Open Sans and compare their readability at smaller sizes.\n\n**In Summary:**\n\nWhile technically possible, Calibri 9 is not ideal for resumes due to potential readability issues. Aim for a font size between 10.5 and 12, and prioritize clear, easy-to-read text to make a positive impression. Always print and test your resume to ensure it looks professional and is easy to read.\n",
